article.description: Rookie Vanessa Hayden scored 10 of her career-high 12 points in the second half Saturday night, leading the Minnesota Lynx to a 78-70 victory over the Detroit Shock.
article.headline: Hayden keys second-half comeback
article.linkText: Rookie Hayden scores 12 as Lynx stalk visiting Shock
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The Minnesota Lynx's Vanessa Hayden delivered
her finest game as a pro against the defending WNBA champions.

Hayden scored 10 of her career-high 12 points in the second half
Saturday night, leading the Lynx to a 78-70 victory over the
Detroit Shock.

Minnesota's rookie center -- one of two first-round draft picks
for the Lynx -- sparked a second-half comeback by shooting 6-for-10,
blocking three shots and taking a key charge with just under three
minutes remaining and the Lynx holding a three-point lead. Hayden's
dominant inside play frustrated the Shock, who shot 36 percent from
the field in the second half after making half of their shots
before the break.

"That's what we anticipated her being able to do, healthy,"
Lynx coach Suzie McConnell Serio said.

Hayden missed the start of the season while recovering from a
severe ankle injury, but has worked her way into shape and into
Minnesota's lineup.

"It was a matter of conditioning and confidence, of getting out
there and feeling like I'm supposed to be out there," said Hayden,
who played a career-high 19 minutes.

Katie Smith led the Lynx with 27 points, shooting 4-for-5 from
3-point range. Helen Darling added season highs of 11 points and
nine assists.

Detroit led by as many as 10 points early in the second half,
but the game turned when Hayden re-entered with 14 minutes
remaining and Minnesota trailing 58-48. Hayden didn't leave the
floor again, and she won the battle with reigning rookie of the year
Cheryl Ford as the Lynx outscored Detroit 30-12 the rest of the
way.

"Vanessa Hayden outplayed me," said Ford, who had 13 points
and 10 rebounds. "She got whatever position she wanted, and she
scored, so I will take the blame for that."

Hayden keyed a 17-4 run with four baskets, including a 7-foot
runner that gave Minnesota a 64-62 lead. She and fellow rookie
Nicole Ohlde forced Detroit turnovers by drawing offensive fouls in
the final three minutes. In the span, the Shock committed nine
second-half turnovers after just four in the first half

"Coming out in the second half, we didn't do a good job of
slowing it down," Detroit guard Deanna Nolan said. "They came out
and had confidence in themselves, and with that confidence, they
could come back and win it."

Merlakia Jones led Detroit with 16 points in a reserve role.
Swin Cash, Ford and Nolan finished with 13 points apiece.

Jones made her first six shots and scored 12 first-half points
to help the Shock overcome an early six-point deficit and take a
40-31 lead at the break. But Hayden's play in the second half was
the difference.

"They kept taking it to Vanessa, but as soon as they made
contact with her, the first thing they saw was her in the lane,"
Lynx forward Tamika Williams said. "They're just not used to
seeing that."
